\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bushfire activity records
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This experiment uses the same bushfire activity datasets used in the previous
 chapter.
 Additionally, the definitions of bushfire event remain the same.
 A bushfire event in DELWP's dataset refers to any event that burnt more
 than 10.000 hectares.
 Peril Aus database defines a bushfire event when it generates several reports.
 Using these definitions, both datasets are comparable as demonstrated in
 the previous chapter.
 Only the season DJF was since other seasons have scarce extreme bushfire
 occurrences.
 The period of analysis was 1961-2010.
 Consistent bushfire occurences data was available starting from this year.
 This allowed to perform the correlation analysis between the four groups
 of data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bushfire danger metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantification of bushfire danger required the computation of FFDI and
 VSBI in Victoria.
 The FFDI provides daily values of bushfire danger.
 However, this research used a seasonal perspective approach.
 Thus, it was necessary to compute seasonal metrics of bushfire danger based
 on the FFDI.
 There are two common seasonal metrics of this index.
 The first metric is a cumulative sum of daily FFDI values (FFDIcum).
 The second metric is the number of days with FFDI values greater than an
 arbitrary threshold.
 For this investigation the chosen threshold was 25 (FFDI>25).
 Values above this threshold reflect days with very high to catastrophic
 bushfire danger.
 The data used for the correlation analysis was time series of FFDIcum and
 FFDI>25 in Victoria.
 On the other hand, the VSBI requires normalized climate data averaged—summed
 in the case of precipitation—for each variable.
 A time series of VSBI values was a third input of bushfire danger in the
 correlation analysis.
 The methodology section presents the descripion of the VSBI formulation.
\end_layout

