\begin_layout Standard
This chapter aims to establish the relationship between bushfire predictands
 and predictors.
 Moreover, the investigation explores how the relationship evolves from
 spring to summer in Victoria.
 The investigation used a linear correlation analysis to establish these
 relationships.
 There were four groups of data compiled or generated in this investigation.
 These groups are bushfire activity records, seasonal bushfire danger metrics,
 climate variables and indices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlation analysis used data from spring (SON) and summer (DJF).
 The exception was for bushfire activity records.
 The bushfire definition used accounts for extreme events.
 These events are not common in other seasons than DJF.
 Therefore, the number of events in spring was too low to include them in
 the analysis.
 For example, the DELWP database regitered 31 events during the December-January
-February (DJF) season over the period 1961-2011.
 The other three seasons of the year registered only 11 events during the
 same period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The period of analysis was 1980-2010 and 1974-2010.
 For the first period of analysis used only weather station data.
 For the second period used weather station and reanalysis data.
 The SAM index—AAO— was excluded from the analysis for the second period.
 The AAO did not show a significant correlation with most variables in the
 first period.
 The VSBI was sensitive to the biases in precipitation in the 20CR data.
 Therefore, precipitation from weather stations substituted the 20CR data
 for the period 1974-2010.
 The results highlight the statistically significant results at the 5% level.
\end_layout

