\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI values computed with weather station data depict more extreme seasonal
 bushfire weather for Victoria than using reanalysis data.
 This difference is likely to occur for several reasons.
 FFDI variables from renalysis data do not correspond exactly to surface
 values.
 Reanalysis data is available from 1000 h-Pa level.
 The FFDI computed with weather station data use values at 3 pm.
 Yet, reanalysis data for FFDI variables is available on at 6-hourly intervals.
 This limited the availability of data to 4 pm values.
 Additionally, there are intrinsic limitations in the reanalysis dataset
 already discussed in Chapter 2.
 Yet, simple linear scaling tecniques demonstrated to adjust the biases
 without signifincatly altering the correlations.
 However, the seasonal bushfire danger determined for this region might
 vary if we use a different bushfire index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though the use of an alternitve index might show a different seasonal
 bushfire danger trend, the difference is unlikely to be significant.
 A study performed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
