key "Dowdy2009"

\end_inset

 determined that the FFDI is comparable to the Canadian Fire Weather Index
 (FWI) for Australian conditions.
 The FWI is an internationally recognized index (citations) that could be
 the most reliable source of comparison.
 Therefore, the results obtained using the FFDI can considered representitive
 of bushfire weather conditions in Victoria.
 In spite that an alternative index might not significantly change the results,
 the use of only mean values of the 20CR brings non-quantified undertainties
 to the seasonal bushfire danger computation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average state of the atmosphere represented by the mean values of the
 20CR derives from the mean of 56 model realizations (citation).
 Every realization represents an equally possible state of the atmosphere
 (citation).
 Thus, the seasonal bushfire danger results computed have a degree of uncertaint
y that has not been quantified.
 The bias-correction results are therefore only valid for one possible state
 of the atmosphere.
 However, most 20CR realizations show an increasing trend in temperature
 consistent with an atmosphere under a global warming process (citations).
 The computed FFDI seasonal metrics‚—which largely depend on temeprature—are
 in agreement with this increasing trend.
 This trend is more pronounced using weather station data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The increasing trend in seasonal bushfire danger computations for Victoria
