\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seasonal bushfire weather has been explored using seasonal metrics of the
 FDDI (FFDI_cum and FFDI>50) in Victoria for the 20th century.
 For the second half of the century, the relationship between seasonal bushfire
 potential, fire activity and a proposed alternative simple bushfire weather
 index has been investigated.
 The skill for this new index, its variables and ENSO indices to forecast
 seasonal bushfire weather has also been investigated.
 The proposed index has a low skill to forecast bushfire weather (0.3), although
 shows a moderate capability to represent simultaneous bushfire weather
 (compared to seasonal metrics of the FFDI) and fire activity.
 In fact, it relationship to fire activity is actually slightly better than
 the one obtained with the seasonal metrics of the FFDI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows us to present an alternative index to investigate past and future
 seasonal bushfire weather which is more simple to calculate than the FFDI.
 Further refinement of the index would involve the incorporation of a parameter
 that accounts for seasonal frontal activity during the concurrent bushfire
 season.
 It is also important to mention that since it has already been established
 that the IOD preconditions bushfire seasons in Victoria, and we found not
 much skill in ENSO to forecast bushfire weather (but it does have skill
 to forecast precipitation) the refinement of the index might incorporate
 an IOD parameter that has skill to forecast temperature and relative humidity
 behaviour.
 
\end_layout

